[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Somebody produced a finished movie, fully narrated and scored for 2 cents, and there was no studio behind it. The thing that made the whole video was the same coding assistant you already used to write software. It\'s called Open Montage, and the idea'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'is that your AI coding assistant, the same Claude code or cursor you write software in, turns into a full video production studio. You describe what you want in plain English, and the agent'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'handles the entire production from the research and the script all the way to the finished rendered video. It went up on GitHub around 3 months ago, and it\'s already past 25,000 stars, it hit number'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'one trending, and it\'s open source under AGPL. The surprising part is who\'s behind it. Mostly one developer who works at Microsoft building this on the side, and those example videos I'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'mentioned cost cents because the software itself is free, and you only pay the AI providers underneath when you use them at all. Enjoying this so far? Subscribe to the YouTube channel and grab the free daily'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'newsletter at indiehacker.news. New deep dive every weekday. Scroll the readme, and the first thing you get is proof, a row of finished videos the thing actually made. There\'s'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'a cinematic sci-fi trailer where the script and the motion clips were all generated, soundtrack included. Then a little Pixar-style short about a banana who makes a friend, six AI clips'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'stitched together with their own narration and music, and the whole thing cost $1.33 to produce. Keep going, and it gets sillier in the best way, a 70-second history piece on the library at Alexandria, hand-built scene by'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'scene, total cost 2 cents. A product ad made with a single AI key for 69 cents. A couple of Ghibli-style animations for about 15 cents each. And right at the bottom, maybe the most useful part, you'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'can paste in a YouTube video you already like and have it build a grounded plan for your own version instead of staring at a blank prompt. So, how is this different from the AI'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'video tools everyone already knows? Something like Runway or Google\'s VEO gives you one clip from one prompt, which is amazing for a few seconds, and then it\'s on you to assemble an actual video. A lot of the so-called free AI'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'video stacks really just mean animate a few still images and call it a movie. The locked-up commercial tools keep the whole pipeline behind a login and a subscription. Open Montage\'s bet is the'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'opposite. The part a real production team would charge you for runs as open code you can read and change. Put the scale on cards. 12 full pipelines, 52 separate tools, and over 500 skill files teaching the agent how'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'to use all of it. And the cheapest finished video on that Redmi, start to end, came in at 2 cents. Look at what it can actually make, and the range is genuinely wide. Those 12'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'pipelines are each a complete recipe for a different kind of video. The explainer one handles a topic end to end, from the research through to the animated visuals. The cinematic one builds'

[03:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'trailers and moody teasers. The clip factory takes one long video, say a 2-hour podcast, and cuts it into a batch of ranked short clips for social. And the one that stands out, a real'

[03:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'documentary pipeline that doesn\'t fake it with stills, it pulls actual stock and archival footage from places like archive.org and NASA, ranks the clips by how well they match, and edits them into'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'a true montage. Want to be featured? Pitch your open-source repo at indiehacker.news/apply and get in front of thousands of builders.'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Now, the parts that make it feel less like a toy. Before it writes a single line of script, the agent goes and does live web research. It\'ll run 15 to 25 searches across YouTube, Reddit, and the wider news web, so the video is grounded'

[04:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'in real current facts instead of made-up ones. That paste a reference trick from earlier is reference-driven under the hood. It actually reverse-engineers the pacing and structure of the clip you'

[04:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'give it. There are real quality gates, too. A check that refuses to ship something that looks like a slideshow, plus a self-review after rendering that actually inspects the frames and the audio levels.'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'And there\'s budget governance baked in, cost estimates up front, and spending caps, so the agent can\'t quietly run up a giant bill. Architecturally, the interesting choice is that there\'s no orchestrator program'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'running the show. Your coding agent is the orchestrator. The repo hands it a set of instruction files, the pipelines are written as YAML manifests, and the know-how lives in plain markdown skill'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'files, and Python is just the box of tools the agent reaches into. When it\'s time to actually render, it picks between two engines, Remotion, which is React-based, for data-driven'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'explainers, and a more motion-graphics-oriented HTML engine for the kinetic stuff with FFmpeg doing the post-production. And every tool choice runs through a scored selector that'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'ranks the providers across seven axes like quality and cost, then logs why it picked what it picked. Getting it running is about as boring as it gets, which is the point. You clone the repo, you run make setup, and that'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'pulls in the whole tool chain and the node renderer, plus a free offline voice so you can make something for nothing. Then you literally just open the folder in your coding assistant and tell it in a sentence what video you want. That\'s'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the whole interface. There\'s no app and no timeline to learn. You just talk to your agent and it takes it from there. Here\'s the part I think gets under sold. You can run this whole stack without'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'paying anyone a cent. Out of the box, it gives you a free offline voice called Piper that genuinely sounds like a person, not a robot. For visuals, it leans on those same open archives, real public domain footage, so even the'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'documentary path costs nothing. And the actual render runs on remote motion right there on your own machine, so nothing you make has to leave it and nothing meters you. Then if you do want the fancier stuff,'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the flux images or the premium voices, you just add an API key and that provider lights up. Free is the floor here, not a crippled demo. So, who is this actually for?'

[06:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Be honest about the rough edges first. It\'s a harness, not a polished app. You drive all of it by talking to a coding agent, so there\'s a real learning curve before anything renders. The generation'

[06:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'still wanders, which is exactly why it keeps stopping to ask you to approve the big creative calls. And calling it free needs an asterisk. The free path is genuinely real, but the prettiest output still spends money once you flip on the'

[07:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'paid providers. The detail that really sticks with me though is that the readme has a whole section written not for you, but for the AI agent that might be reading it, teaching it how to run the studio on its own. That\'s the real'

[07:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'shift. Making a video stops being a craft you outsource and turns into one more thing you can just ask your agent to go do. If you already live inside a coding assistant all day, this is the'

[07:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'one to clone this weekend and point at a weird idea.'
